<title>How to use external antenna on Wemos D1 mini pro – surface mount rework video</title>
<link>http://raspi.tv/2017/how-to-use-external-antenna-on-wemos-d1-mini-pro-surface-mount-rework-video</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >http://raspi.tv/2017/how-to-use-external-antenna-on-wemos-d1-mini-pro-surface-mount-rework-video</guid>
<description>&lt;div class=&quot;left-thumbnail&quot;&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;150&quot; src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-150x150.jpg&quot; class=&quot;attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image&quot; alt=&quot;Wemos D1 mini pro - how to move the zero ohm resistor to use an external antenna&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-150x150.jpg 150w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-300x300.jpg 300w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-768x768.jpg 768w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-96x96.jpg 96w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-24x24.jpg 24w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-36x36.jpg 36w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-48x48.jpg 48w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500-64x64.jpg 64w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-thumbnail_1500.jpg 1500w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In &lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/2017/wireless-remote-sensing-with-wemos-d1-mini-arduino-ide-raspberry-pi-and-lighttpd-web-server&quot;&gt;my previous blog post&lt;/a&gt; I showed how I used several Wemos D1 mini to make a network of wireless temperature sensors around RasPiTV HQ. These litle boards are based on the ESP8266 microcontroller with built-in WiFi.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a Pro version available too. One of its main benefits is that you can attach an external WiFi antenna for greater range. This is an optional feature, and it does require some delicate surgery to reroute the antenna signal from the built-in ceramic antenna, to the external socket. It’s not especially difficult once you know what you’re doing, but it is very small if you’ve not worked at this size before.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9954&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-D1-mini-pro_700.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-D1-mini-pro_700.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Zero-Ohm link on Wemos D1 mini pro&quot; width=&quot;700&quot; height=&quot;392&quot; class=&quot;size-full wp-image-9954&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-D1-mini-pro_700.jpg 700w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Wemos-D1-mini-pro_700-300x168.jpg 300w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Zero-Ohm link on Wemos D1 mini pro&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a small surface mount (0603) Zero Ohm resistor (sometimes called a link) which needs to be rotated to enable this change. It is a challenging procedure simply because of the size of the component. I messed it up first time, but treated that as a rehearsal. This is the performance, and it went quite well. I caught the whole thing on video and this is a video post. Enjoy!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;embed-youtube&quot;&gt;&lt;iframe class=&quot;youtube-player&quot; type=&quot;text/html&quot; width=&quot;695&quot; height=&quot;421&quot; src=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/embed/3lHoG1mu7hY?version=3&amp;amp;rel=1&amp;amp;fs=1&amp;amp;autohide=2&amp;amp;showsearch=0&amp;amp;showinfo=1&amp;amp;iv_load_policy=1&amp;amp;wmode=transparent&quot; allowfullscreen=&quot;true&quot;&gt;[embedded content]&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
