<item>
<title>RasPiO Portsplus Picademy – NEW product.</title>
<link>http://raspi.tv/2016/raspio-portsplus-picademy-new-product</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >http://raspi.tv/2016/raspio-portsplus-picademy-new-product</guid>
<description>&lt;div class=&quot;left-thumbnail&quot;&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;150&quot; src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-150x150.jpg&quot; class=&quot;attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image&quot; alt=&quot;Portsplus Picademy edition&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-150x150.jpg 150w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-300x300.jpg 300w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-768x768.jpg 768w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-96x96.jpg 96w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-24x24.jpg 24w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-36x36.jpg 36w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-48x48.jpg 48w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500-64x64.jpg 64w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned-thumbnail_1500.jpg 1500w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you’ve been hanging around the RasPi.TV blog for a while you’ll have heard of the &lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/portsplus&quot;&gt;RasPiO Portsplus&lt;/a&gt; board. It’s a little PCB with the Pi’s GPIO port numbers on that you can use to avoid counting pins when wiring up your GPIO projects.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1128&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/RasPiO_portsplus_on_Pi2_7001.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1128&quot; src=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/RasPiO_portsplus_on_Pi2_7001.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;RasPiO Portsplus on Raspberry Pi 2B&quot; width=&quot;350&quot; height=&quot;270&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;RasPiO Portsplus on Raspberry Pi 2B&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A few months ago I was visiting Pi Towers. Ben Nuttall mentioned that they use the Portsplus at Picademy, but sometimes people put them on the wrong way up and it causes confusion. The original Portsplus has GPIO port numbers one one side and pin numbers on the other side. It was designed to appeal to both ‘camps’ since both schemes are in use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That left me with a decision to make…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;‘Fork’ the product and bring out a new one alongside the original&lt;/li&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;li&gt;Make a new one and obsolete the original&lt;/li&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;li&gt;Do nothing&lt;/li&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;I like choices, so in the end I decided to create a Portsplus Picademy edition. Here it is…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1742&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned_1500.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1742&quot; src=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-cleaned_700.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Portplus Picademy edition Raspberry Pi Port Identification board&quot; width=&quot;700&quot; height=&quot;417&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Portplus Picademy edition Raspberry Pi Port Identification board&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1744&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption alignright&quot; readability=&quot;33&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-bothsides-cleaned_700.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-medium wp-image-1744&quot; src=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Portsplus-Picademy-bothsides-cleaned_700-177x300.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Portplus Picademy edition both sides&quot; width=&quot;177&quot; height=&quot;300&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Portplus Picademy edition GPIO numbers one side, Alt functions other side&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1127&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption alignright&quot; readability=&quot;33&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/RasPiO_portsplus_both_sides_7001.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-medium wp-image-1127&quot; src=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/RasPiO_portsplus_both_sides_7001-272x300.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;RasPiO Portsplus GPIO numbers one side, Pin numbers other side&quot; width=&quot;272&quot; height=&quot;300&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;RasPiO Portsplus GPIO numbers one side, Pin numbers other side&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It also has rather fancy gold-plated lettering for RasPiO and Picademy. It should appeal to hardware hackers as well because it has the alternative functions on the reverse side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At just 1mm thick, it leaves plenty of space for attaching your wires. It’s thick enough not to feel flimsy, but thin enough not to be clunky.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Where and How Much?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/portsplus&quot;&gt;RasPiO Portsplus product page is here&lt;/a&gt;. You can also grab one right here by clicking the PayPal buttons below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They cost £2 + £1 shipping anywhere in the world.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can use it as an attractive key-fob as well (split-ring not supplied).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1129&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/RasPiO_portsplus-keyring_7001-e1429862290979.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1129&quot; src=&quot;http://rasp.io/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/RasPiO_portsplus-keyring_7001-e1429862290979.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;RasPiO Portsplus as a keyfob&quot; width=&quot;324&quot; height=&quot;147&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;RasPiO Portsplus as a keyfob&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
