<item>
<title>Raspberry Pi Family photo update November 2016</title>
<link>http://raspi.tv/2016/raspberry-pi-family-photo-update-november-2016</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >http://raspi.tv/2016/raspberry-pi-family-photo-update-november-2016</guid>
<description>&lt;div class=&quot;left-thumbnail&quot;&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;150&quot; src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-150x150.jpg&quot; class=&quot;attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image&quot; alt=&quot;Raspberry Pi Family Photo CC-BY-SA 4 RasPi.TV credit&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-150x150.jpg 150w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-96x96.jpg 96w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-24x24.jpg 24w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-36x36.jpg 36w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-48x48.jpg 48w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-64x64.jpg 64w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since the February 2016 launch of the Raspberry Pi 3B there have been three new Pi released. They’re not major revisions, but they are different. Around May the A+ got a 512 MB memory upgrade. I pre-ordered one immediately and it materialised at the end of August. But that alone didn’t warrant a new family photo.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also in May the new &lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/2016/raspberry-pi-zero-1-3-with-camera-port&quot;&gt;Pi Zero 1.3 with camera port&lt;/a&gt; was released.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But it was last week’s arrival of the &lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/2016/new-raspberry-pi-2b-1-2-with-pi3-bcm2837-processor&quot;&gt;new Pi2B 1.2 with BCM2837 processor&lt;/a&gt; that made me decide it was time to get the camera out. I was wondering when to schedule it for publication, when I saw this…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align=&quot;center&quot; readability=&quot;7.7189189189189&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot; data-width=&quot;550&quot; readability=&quot;9.0810810810811&quot;&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;While not bat-herding today, we’ve been checking our slide rules. We’ve sold ELEVEN MILLION RASPBERRY PIS. Forward the Foundation!&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;— Raspberry Pi (@Raspberry_Pi) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/Raspberry_Pi/status/801408873458532352&quot;&gt;November 23, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;…so &lt;strong&gt;right now seemed like the perfect time for a family photo&lt;/strong&gt;, celebrating 11 million Pi sales. You can click on the image for a 1500px version. This photo is released on a CC-BY-SA 4 license, with the only condition being that the RasPi.TV credit stays intact. Other than that it may be used freely. If anyone needs a higher resolution version for commercial purposes, get in touch (alex AT raspi.tv) and we’ll work something out.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9821&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_1500.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Raspberry Pi Family Photo CC-BY-SA 4 RasPi.TV credit&quot; width=&quot;700&quot; height=&quot;649&quot; class=&quot;size-full wp-image-9821&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700.jpg 700w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Pi-Family-Photo-Master-Nov-2016_700-300x278.jpg 300w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Raspberry Pi Family Photo CC-BY-SA 4 RasPi.TV credit&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The small numbers are the board ID numbers as reported by&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;cat /proc/cpuinfo&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
