</item>
<item>
<title>How to Flash an SD Card with Larger than 4GB Image – Raspbian September 2016 update</title>
<link>http://raspi.tv/2016/how-to-flash-an-sd-card-with-4gb-files-like-raspbian-september-2016-update</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >http://raspi.tv/2016/how-to-flash-an-sd-card-with-4gb-files-like-raspbian-september-2016-update</guid>
<description>&lt;div class=&quot;left-thumbnail&quot;&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;150&quot; src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-150x150.png&quot; class=&quot;attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image&quot; alt=&quot;Flash an SD card larger than 4 GB for raspberry pi&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-150x150.png 150w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-300x300.png 300w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-768x768.png 768w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-96x96.png 96w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-24x24.png 24w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-36x36.png 36w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-48x48.png 48w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB-64x64.png 64w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/flash-sd-card-greater-4GB.png 1000w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yesterday (28 Sep 2016) a new version of Raspbian was released with a brand new skin called PIXEL. I downloaded it on my Mac and tried to unzip it in the usual way. It threw an error, so I assumed the download was faulty and downloaded again. But the error persisted. GAH!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9574&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Alex-Mac.png&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Alex-Mac.png&quot; alt=&quot;Unzipping error on Mac&quot; width=&quot;512&quot; height=&quot;151&quot; class=&quot;size-full wp-image-9574&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Alex-Mac.png 512w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Alex-Mac-300x88.png 300w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Unzipping error on Mac&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My friend &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/winkleink&quot;&gt;Albert Hickey&lt;/a&gt; (who runs the &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/EghamJam&quot;&gt;Egham Jam&lt;/a&gt;) had a similar issue on Windows…&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9575&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Albert-Windows.png&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Albert-Windows.png&quot; alt=&quot;Unzipping error on Windows&quot; width=&quot;450&quot; height=&quot;262&quot; class=&quot;size-full wp-image-9575&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Albert-Windows.png 450w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Albert-Windows-300x175.png 300w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 450px) 100vw, 450px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Unzipping error on Windows&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/biglesp&quot;&gt;Les Pounder&lt;/a&gt; said it &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/biglesp/status/781065929564286976&quot;&gt;worked fine in Ubuntu&lt;/a&gt; though.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Didn’t Unzip on Pi&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I tried unzipping it on a Pi, but that failed too. BOO! However, it was soon revealed on twitter what the issue was…&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Files Over 4 GigaBytes Need a Modern Unzipper&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The unzipped Raspbian image is larger than 4 Gigabytes&lt;/strong&gt;, which means the default unzipping software cannot cope. So I took Simon’s recommendation and looked in the App Store for “The Unarchiver”. It turned out to be a free app, which installed easily…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9579&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.17.55.png&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.17.55-300x121.png&quot; alt=&quot;The Unarchiver - FREE in the app store&quot; width=&quot;300&quot; height=&quot;121&quot; class=&quot;size-medium wp-image-9579&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.17.55-300x121.png 300w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.17.55.png 432w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;The Unarchiver – FREE in the app store&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I used it to unzip the 1.52 GB “2016-09-23-raspbian-jessie.zip” file to its full 4.35 GB as “2016-09-23-raspbian-jessie.img”&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9580&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.30.22.png&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.30.22-300x42.png&quot; alt=&quot;Zipped and unzipped Raspbian&quot; width=&quot;300&quot; height=&quot;42&quot; class=&quot;size-medium wp-image-9580&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.30.22-300x42.png 300w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Screen-Shot-2016-09-29-at-08.30.22.png 616w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Zipped and unzipped Raspbian&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;7-Zip Works for Windows&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you’re using Windows, you can use 7-Zip instead. &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.7-zip.org/download.html&quot;&gt;You can download 7-Zip here.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“Great!” I then thought. “I’ll shove the 4.35 GB .img file on a memory stick and use a Pi to flash it to the micro-SD card with dd”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Foiled Again&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But the file refused to copy onto the memory stick (something to do with the stick’s format), so that idea was shelved. Could I use &lt;code&gt;dd&lt;/code&gt; directly? I don’t really like using &lt;code&gt;dd&lt;/code&gt; on my main computer. It’s not by accident that it’s nicknamed “destroy disk”, which isn’t something I want to do to my work machine. I sometimes use it in a Ubuntu virtual machine on my Mac, but…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Etcher is the New Way&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;…then I remembered &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/MattRichardson&quot;&gt;Matt Richardson&lt;/a&gt; recently mentioned &lt;strong&gt;Etcher&lt;/strong&gt;, which is a lovely piece of FREE software that handles the SD flashing process for you. It not only works well and has a lovely interface, but there are versions for Linux, Mac and Windows. So finally we have a system that works on all three major platforms. YAY! &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.etcher.io/&quot;&gt;You can find and download Etcher here.&lt;/a&gt; (It will also write an image directly from a .Zip file if you prefer to do that, but it is slower.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_9589&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption aligncenter&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/etcher-small.gif&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/etcher-small.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Etcher really IS this simple to use&quot; width=&quot;695&quot; height=&quot;327&quot; class=&quot;size-full wp-image-9589&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Etcher really IS this simple to use&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Etcher installed beautifully and worked perfectly the first time. It also has built-in safeguards to prevent you from accidentally destroying your hard drive. Using a USB3 card reader/writer, it took 12 minutes and 21 seconds to flash the new Raspbian image “2016-09-23-raspbian-jessie.img” to a micro-SD card.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And then I was able to have a play with the latest OS and see the new PIXEL UI improvements. But that’s a story for another day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;In Summary&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The new Raspbian is 4.35 GB and may not unzip without using a newer “unzipper” than the defaults on OSX and Windows.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unzip Raspbian images &amp;gt;4GB with The Unarchiver on OSX, 7-Zip on Windows, it should “just work” in Ubuntu.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Flash Raspbian images with Etcher – works on all 3 platforms (but not yet on Pi)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled&quot;&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing&quot;&gt;
