<item>
<title>RasPiO Pro Hat  – Putting Pi Ports in Perfect Positions for Productive Play</title>
<link>http://raspi.tv/2016/raspio-pro-hat-putting-pi-ports-in-perfect-positions-for-productive-play</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >http://raspi.tv/2016/raspio-pro-hat-putting-pi-ports-in-perfect-positions-for-productive-play</guid>
<description>&lt;div class=&quot;left-thumbnail&quot;&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;150&quot; height=&quot;150&quot; src=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-150x150.jpg&quot; class=&quot;attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image&quot; alt=&quot;RasPiO Pro Hat&quot; srcset=&quot;http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-150x150.jpg 150w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-96x96.jpg 96w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-24x24.jpg 24w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-36x36.jpg 36w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-48x48.jpg 48w, http://raspi.tv/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ProHat-KS-graphic_1500-64x64.jpg 64w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px&quot;/&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Today I launched the &lt;a href=&quot;http://kck.st/1WdN3hM&quot;&gt;RasPiO Pro Hat on Kickstarter&lt;/a&gt;. It’s a Raspberry Pi Hat for GPIO tinkering (it goes perfectly with GPIO Zero). It arranges the GPIO ports in numerical order around a mini-breadboard, which, to my knowledge, has not been done before.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It also replaces the RasPiO Breakout Pro (now end of life) because it protects all the ports from over-current and over/under-voltage as well. It should prove a very useful board for GPIO tinkering and education. Have a look at the video and pop on over to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://kck.st/1WdN3hM&quot;&gt;RasPiO Pro Hat campaign page&lt;/a&gt; to take a look…&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;KickStarter Tracker With Graphing&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As usual, I’m tracking and graphing the campaign’s progress using the Python scripts I developed on a Raspberry Pi. They’re running on my web server now, but they work equally well on a Pi. Here’s the output (updates every five minutes)…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://plot.ly/~alexeames/690/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; title=&quot;RasPiO Pro Hat KS Tracker £ VS hours&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://plot.ly/~alexeames/690.png&quot; alt=&quot;RasPiO Pro Hat KS Tracker £ VS hours&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; onerror=&quot;this.onerror=null;this.src='https://plot.ly/404.png';&quot;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If the &lt;a href=&quot;http://kck.st/1WdN3hM&quot;&gt;RasPiO Pro Hat looks interesting to you, please consider backing the project.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
